definition.value: A glycosyl group formed formally by loss of the hydroxy group from the reducing-end anomeric carbon of alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo.
An S-conjugate in which the mercapto hydrogen of L-cysteinylglycine has been replaced by an N-hydroxy-2-(indol-3-yl)ethanimidoyl group.
A monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and sulfino groups of 3-sulfinopropionic acid. Major microspecies at pH 7.3
A thiol that is toluene in which one of the methyl hydrogens has been replaced by a sulfanyl group.
A thioaldehyde that is benzaldehyde in which the oxygen has been replaced by divalent sulfur.
An S-conjugate in which the mercapto hydrogen of L-cysteinylglycine has been replaced by a cyano(indol-3-yl)methyl group.
A member of the class of aldehydes that is glycolaldehyde in which the hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by a triphosphate group.
A metalloporphyrin that is sirohydrochlorin in which the four nitrogen atoms are bound to a central nickel atom.
A steroidal-CoA(4-) obtained by deprotonation of phosphate and diphosphate functions of ursodeoxycholoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.

A glycosyl group formed formally by loss of the hydroxy group from the reducing-end anomeric carbon of alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->3)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo.
Any mammalian metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in Papio hamadryas.
An cyanohydrin that is acetonitrile in which one of the hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxy group.

A carbohydrate derivative in which a tetrasaccharide derivative consisting of an alpha-D-rhamnose residue, two N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues and a methyl N-formyl-alpha-D-perosaminide residue linked sequentially (1->2), (1->3) and (1->2) is linked to a protein, normally via a 3,4-diaminocyclobutane-1,2-dione-based linker attached to position 4 of the rhamnose residue at the non-reducing end.
A cholestanoid that is cholestanol substituted by a hydroxy group at position 24S.
A cholestanoid that is cholestanol which is substituted by a hydroxy group at position 26 and has R-configuration at position 25.

A carbohydrate derivative in which a tetrasaccharide derivative consisting of an alpha-D-rhamnose residue, five N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues and a methyl N-formyl-alpha-D-perosaminide residue, all linked sequentially (1->2), is linked to a protein, normally via a 3,4-diaminocyclobutane-1,2-dione-based linker attached to position 4 of the rhamnose residue at the non-reducing end.
An amino tetrasaccharide consisting of an alpha-D-mannose residue and three N-formyl-alpha-D-perosamine residues linked sequentially (1->2), (1->3) and (1->2).
The glycosyl group formed formally by loss of the hydroxy group from the reducing-end anomeric carbon of alpha-D-Manp-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->3)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo-(1->2)-alpha-D-Rhap4NFo.
Exoenzyme C3 Transferase from Clostridium botulinum, commonly used to selectively inactivate the GTPases RhoA, RhoB, and RhoC, both in vivo and in vitro

A D-tryptophan derivative obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of D-tryptophan with the amino group of (quinoxalin-6-yl)methylidenehydrazide. It directly targets the Rho GEF binding domain, thereby preventing Rho from interacting with its GEFs

A hydrochloride salt resulting from the reaction of (S)-2-methyl-1-(4-methylisoquinoline-5-sulfonyl)-1,4-diazepane with 2 mol eq. of hydrogen chloride. An ATP-competitive inhibitor of Rho kinase (ROCK).

A polyether that is 4,7,10-trioxatridecane substituted at positions 1 and 13 by an amino group and a 3-carboxypropanamido group respectively. Flexible and hydrophilic, it is used as an extended linker in solid-phase immunoassays.
A metalloporphyrin that is sirohydrochlorin a,c-diamide in which the four nitrogen atoms are bound to a central nickel atom.
A six-membered oligopeptide comprising L-leucine, L-serine, L-glutamic acid, L-threonine, L-threonine and D-leucine residues coupled in sequence.
A seven-membered oligopeptide comprising L-leucine, L-serine, L-glutamic acid, L-threonine, L-glutamic acid, L-threonine and D-leucine residues coupled in sequence.
A metalloporphyrin having nickel as the central metal atom; an intermediate in the biosynthesis of coenzyme F430 in methanogenic bacteria.
A 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the 3-carboxy group of 3-carboxy-3-hydroxypropanoic acid.
A steroid glucosiduronic acid that is 17-epiestriol having a single beta-D-glucuronic acid residue attached at position 3.
A steroid glucosiduronic acid that is 17-epiestriol having a single beta-D-glucuronic acid residue attached at position 17.
A steroid glucosiduronic acid that is 17-epiestriol having a single beta-D-glucuronic acid residue attached at position 16.
A nona-2,4,6-trienal in which all three double bonds adopt trans-configurations.
A steroid glucosiduronic acid that is 16-epiestriol having a single beta-D-glucuronic acid residue attached at position 3.
